<section id="introduction">
      <h2>Introduction to the Chinese Calendar</h2>
      <p>The Chinese calendar is a <strong>lunisolar</strong> system that tracks both the moon's phases and the sun's position. Unlike the purely solar Gregorian calendar, it incorporates lunar months (new moon to new moon) while using solar markers to stay aligned with the seasons. This dual nature made it indispensable for agriculture, festival scheduling, astrological calculation, and daily planning for thousands of years.</p>
      <p>The calendar operates on two parallel tracks: the <strong>lunar month system</strong> governing festivals and daily life, and the <strong>sexagenary cycle</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">干支</span>) of Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches governing astrological and cosmological reckoning. Together they form one of the most sophisticated timekeeping systems in human history.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="origins">
      <h2>Historical Origins</h2>
      <p>Evidence from <strong>Shang Dynasty</strong> oracle bones (c. 1600-1046 BCE) reveals calendar notations using the sexagenary cycle to record days. The system of pairing Heavenly Stems with Earthly Branches predates the zodiac animals and represents one of humanity's oldest continuous timekeeping methods.</p>
      <p>By the <strong>Zhou Dynasty</strong> (1046-256 BCE), the calendar was sophisticated enough to predict eclipses and track the positions of major celestial bodies. Court astronomers maintained detailed records and the calendar carried political significance &mdash; the right to promulgate the calendar was a prerogative of the emperor, symbolising his mandate to order time itself.</p>
      <p>The landmark reform came under <strong>Emperor Wu of Han</strong> in 104 BCE, establishing the <em>Taichu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">太初</span>) calendar. This reform fixed the beginning of the year to the first day of the first lunar month (roughly corresponding to late January or February in the Gregorian calendar), a convention that persists today as the basis for <a href="/spring-festival/">Chinese New Year</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="yellow-river-origins">
      <h2>Yellow River Civilisation and the Calendar's Birthplace</h2>
      <p>The Chinese lunisolar calendar is a product of the <strong>Yellow River</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">黃河</span>, <span class="pinyin">Huánghé</span>) Central Plains (<span class="chinese-char">中原</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zhōngyuán</span>) millet-farming civilisation. This is not merely a geographical claim — it is embedded in the calendar's very structure.</p>

      <h3>The 24 Solar Terms as Climatic Evidence</h3>
      <p>The <a href="#solar-terms">24 Solar Terms</a> are calibrated to the <strong>temperate monsoon climate</strong> of the Yellow River basin (approximately 34–38°N latitude). Terms like <span class="chinese-char">大雪</span> (<span class="pinyin">Dàxuě</span>, Major Snow), <span class="chinese-char">小雪</span> (<span class="pinyin">Xiǎoxuě</span>, Minor Snow), <span class="chinese-char">霜降</span> (<span class="pinyin">Shuāngjiàng</span>, Frost Descent), and <span class="chinese-char">大寒</span> (<span class="pinyin">Dàhán</span>, Major Cold) describe phenomena specific to northern temperate regions. These terms have no equivalent in tropical or subtropical environments — they could only have been conceived by people who experienced distinct four-season weather with frost, snow, and dramatic temperature swings.</p>

      <h3>Taosi Observatory — the World's Earliest Large-Scale Astronomical Site</h3>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>The <strong>Taosi archaeological site</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">陶寺</span>, <span class="pinyin">Táosì</span>) in Shanxi Province (c. 2300–1900 BCE, approximately 4,300–3,900 years ago) contains the <strong>world's earliest known large-scale astronomical observatory</strong>. The semi-circular rammed-earth structure features observation slits aligned with sunrise positions at the winter solstice, summer solstice, and equinoxes — proving that systematic solar observation was practised in the Yellow River region during the late Neolithic period.</p>
        <p>The site also yielded a gnomon (<span class="chinese-char">圭表</span>, <span class="pinyin">guībiǎo</span>) — a vertical pole used to measure shadow lengths and determine solstice dates with precision. This instrument remained the foundation of Chinese astronomical measurement for the next three millennia.</p>
        <cite>— Institute of Archaeology, Chinese Academy of Social Sciences; excavation reports 1978–2005</cite>
      </div>

      <h3>Shang Oracle Bones — the First Written Calendar Records</h3>
      <p>Shang Dynasty oracle bones (<span class="chinese-char">甲骨文</span>, <span class="pinyin">jiǎgǔwén</span>, c. 1600–1046 BCE) from Yinxu (<span class="chinese-char">殷墟</span>, Anyang, Henan) contain the earliest written calendar notations, including precise records of solar and lunar cycles. These inscriptions use the sexagenary cycle to record days and contain observations of eclipses, confirming that sophisticated astronomical knowledge was already well-established in the Yellow River heartland.</p>

      <h3>The Central Plains vs. Other Regions</h3>
      <p>While southern and coastal peoples (collectively termed <span class="chinese-char">百越</span>, <span class="pinyin">Bǎiyuè</span>) developed practical <strong>phenological calendars</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">物候曆</span>, <span class="pinyin">wùhòulì</span>) — observing natural signs like flowering, bird migration, and insect emergence to guide agriculture — these were empirical and localised. The Yellow River civilisation uniquely produced:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A <strong>mathematical calendar system</strong> based on astronomical observation and numerical calculation</li>
        <li><strong>Gnomon shadow measurement</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">圭表</span>) as a precision instrument</li>
        <li><strong>Star charts and celestial pole observation</strong> (the Northern Dipper as seasonal marker)</li>
        <li>The <strong>Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天干地支</span>) system of cyclical counting</li>
        <li>The <strong>intercalary month</strong> system to reconcile lunar and solar cycles</li>
      </ul>
      <p>No comparable mathematical-astronomical calendar system arose independently from the Baiyue or other southern peoples. The lunisolar calendar that spread across East Asia is a Central Plains invention.</p>
    </section>

