    <section id="sexagenary-cycle">
      <h2>The Sexagenary Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">六十干支</span>)</h2>
      <p>The sexagenary cycle creates 60 unique combinations by pairing Heavenly Stems with Earthly Branches. Because Yang stems only pair with Yang branches and Yin with Yin, the result is 60 (not 120) combinations. The cycle repeats every 60 years, months, days, and double-hours, providing a multi-layered temporal framework.</p>
      <p>The first combination is Jiǎzǐ (<span class="chinese-char">甲子</span>, Yang Wood Rat). The cycle proceeds: Yǐchǒu, Bǐngyín, Dīngmǎo... until reaching the 60th combination, Guǐhài (<span class="chinese-char">癸亥</span>, Yin Water Pig), before restarting.</p>
      <p>This 60-year cycle is the basis of the <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> system and determines the precise elemental character of each year. For example, 2026 is Bǐngwǔ (<span class="chinese-char">丙午</span>) &mdash; Yang Fire Horse &mdash; the 43rd combination in the current cycle.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="lunisolar">
      <h2>Lunisolar Mechanics</h2>
      <p>Months follow lunar phases: each begins on a new moon and lasts 29 or 30 days (averaging 29.53 days). Twelve lunar months total roughly 354 days &mdash; about 11 days short of the solar year. To prevent the calendar from drifting through the seasons, <strong>intercalary months</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">閏月</span>, rùnyuè) are inserted approximately every three years (seven times in nineteen years, following the Metonic cycle).</p>
      <p>The solar component is tracked through the <strong>24 Solar Terms</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">節氣</span>, jiéqì), which divide the sun's annual path into 24 equal segments of roughly 15 days each. Solar Terms determine which month receives an intercalary insertion and anchor the calendar to the agricultural seasons.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="solar-terms">
      <h2>The 24 Solar Terms (<span class="chinese-char">二十四節氣</span>)</h2>

      <h3>Origins and Historical Development</h3>
      <p>The 24 Solar Terms (<span class="chinese-char">二十四節氣</span>, èrshísì jiéqì) represent one of the most remarkable astronomical achievements of ancient China. The system divides the sun's annual ecliptic path into 24 segments of approximately 15 degrees each, marking the precise rhythm of seasonal change across the year.</p>
      <p>The earliest evidence of solar-term reckoning appears in <strong>Western Zhou</strong> texts (c. 1046&ndash;771 BCE), where four terms &mdash; the two solstices (<span class="chinese-char">冬至</span>, <span class="chinese-char">夏至</span>) and two equinoxes (<span class="chinese-char">春分</span>, <span class="chinese-char">秋分</span>) &mdash; were already used to mark cardinal seasonal points. By the <strong>Spring and Autumn period</strong> (770&ndash;476 BCE), eight terms were in use, adding the four seasonal beginnings (<span class="chinese-char">立春</span>, <span class="chinese-char">立夏</span>, <span class="chinese-char">立秋</span>, <span class="chinese-char">立冬</span>).</p>
      <p>The complete system of 24 terms was codified during the <strong>Warring States period</strong> (475&ndash;221 BCE) and received its canonical formulation in the <em>Huainanzi</em> (<span class="chinese-char">淮南子</span>), compiled under Liu An during the early <strong>Western Han Dynasty</strong> (c. 139 BCE). The chapter <em>Tianwen Xun</em> (<span class="chinese-char">天文訓</span>) describes how the handle of the Northern Dipper (<span class="chinese-char">北斗</span>) points to different directions as it completes its annual rotation, marking each solar term in sequence.</p>
      <p>In 104 BCE, Emperor Wu of Han's <em>Taichu</em> calendar reform formally incorporated all 24 terms into the official state calendar, establishing the framework that would endure for the next two millennia.</p>

      <h3>The Two Categories: Jié and Qì</h3>
      <p>The 24 terms are divided into two alternating categories. The twelve <strong>Jié</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">節</span>, &ldquo;nodes&rdquo;) mark seasonal transitions and serve as boundary markers for the lunar months. The twelve <strong>Qì</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span>, &ldquo;breaths&rdquo; or &ldquo;mid-points&rdquo;) fall in the middle of each month and indicate the season's peak characteristics.</p>
      <p>This distinction carried practical significance: a lunar month was defined by the Jié that began it, and a month lacking a Qì mid-point was designated as the <strong>intercalary month</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">閏月</span>). This elegant rule, established by the <em>Taichu</em> reform and refined in the <strong>Tang Dynasty</strong>, ensured the lunisolar calendar remained aligned with the solar year without arbitrary adjustments.</p>

      <h3>Calculation Methods: Píngqì and Dìngqì</h3>
      <p>Early calendars used the <strong>Píngqì</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">平氣</span>, &ldquo;even division&rdquo;) method, dividing the tropical year into 24 equal time intervals of approximately 15.22 days each. This approach, used from the Han through the early Tang, assumed the sun moved at a constant speed.</p>
      <p>The astronomer-monk <strong>Yì Xíng</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">一行</span>, 683&ndash;727 CE) recognised that the sun's apparent motion is not uniform. His <em>Dayan Calendar</em> (<span class="chinese-char">大衍曆</span>, 729 CE) introduced the <strong>Dìngqì</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">定氣</span>, &ldquo;true solar position&rdquo;) method, calculating each term based on the sun's actual ecliptic longitude at 15-degree intervals. This more accurate method was fully adopted into the official <em>Shoushi Calendar</em> (<span class="chinese-char">授時曆</span>) by <strong>Guo Shoujing</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">郭守敬</span>) in 1281 under the <strong>Yuan Dynasty</strong>. The <em>Shoushi Calendar</em> measured the tropical year at 365.2425 days &mdash; identical to the Gregorian calendar value, yet achieved three centuries earlier.</p>

      <h3>The 24 Terms in Classical Literature</h3>
      <p>The <em>Liji</em> (<span class="chinese-char">禮記</span>, <em>Book of Rites</em>), a pre-Qin text compiled during the <strong>Han Dynasty</strong>, contains the <em>Yueling</em> (<span class="chinese-char">月令</span>, &ldquo;Monthly Ordinances&rdquo;) chapter, which prescribes specific imperial rituals, agricultural activities, and governmental duties for each solar term. During <span class="chinese-char">立春</span> (Start of Spring), the Son of Heaven was to lead his ministers to the eastern suburbs to welcome spring. During <span class="chinese-char">芒種</span> (Grain in Ear), prayers were offered to the mountain spirits for rain.</p>
      <p>The <strong>Song Dynasty</strong> encyclopaedist <strong>Chen Yuanliang</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">陳元靚</span>) compiled the <em>Suishi Guangji</em> (<span class="chinese-char">歲時廣記</span>), documenting the folk customs, dietary practices, and agricultural rituals associated with each solar term. The <strong>Ming Dynasty</strong> agricultural treatise <em>Nongzheng Quanshu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">農政全書</span>, 1639) by <strong>Xu Guangqi</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">徐光啟</span>) further codified the relationship between solar terms and specific farming operations for different regions of China.</p>

