          <tr><td>Qiūfēn</td><td>秋分</td><td>Sep 23</td><td>Qì</td><td>Autumn Equinox &mdash; Second equal day and night. Moon worship ceremonies were held, a precursor to the Mid-Autumn Festival.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hánlù</td><td>寒露</td><td>Oct 8</td><td>Jié</td><td>Cold Dew &mdash; Dew becomes cold. Chrysanthemum wine (<span class="chinese-char">菊花酒</span>) is brewed, a custom recorded in the Han-era <em>Xijing Zaji</em> (<span class="chinese-char">西京雜記</span>).</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Shuāngjiàng</td><td>霜降</td><td>Oct 23</td><td>Qì</td><td>Frost Descent &mdash; First frost appears. Persimmons are harvested and Chinese medicinal herbs are gathered. Military reviews were traditionally held.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lìdōng</td><td>立冬</td><td>Nov 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Start of Winter &mdash; Harvest complete, fields at rest. The emperor offered winter sacrifices. The <em>Yueling</em> prescribes sealing granaries and repairing city walls.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎoxuě</td><td>小雪</td><td>Nov 22</td><td>Qì</td><td>Minor Snow &mdash; Light snowfall begins in the north. Pickling vegetables and curing meats for winter storage commences.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dàxuě</td><td>大雪</td><td>Dec 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Major Snow &mdash; Heavy snowfall. Rivers freeze. The custom of &ldquo;sealing the plough&rdquo; (<span class="chinese-char">封犁</span>) marked the end of the farming year.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dōngzhì</td><td>冬至</td><td>Dec 22</td><td>Qì</td><td>Winter Solstice &mdash; Shortest day. In Zhou and Han times, this was the start of the new year. Grand court ceremonies were held; officials exchanged formal greetings.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎohán</td><td>小寒</td><td>Jan 6</td><td>Jié</td><td>Minor Cold &mdash; Cold intensifies. The &ldquo;Nine Nines&rdquo; counting custom (<span class="chinese-char">數九</span>) begins from the Winter Solstice, tracking 81 days until spring.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dàhán</td><td>大寒</td><td>Jan 20</td><td>Qì</td><td>Major Cold &mdash; Coldest period. <a href="/spring-festival/">Spring Festival</a> preparations commence. The cycle completes and returns to Lìchūn.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>The Solar Terms and the Five Elements</h3>
      <p>Each season of six solar terms corresponds to one of the <a href="/wuxing/">Five Elements</a> (<span class="chinese-char">五行</span>): Spring with Wood, Summer with Fire, Autumn with Metal, and Winter with Water. The transitional periods at the end of each season (roughly 18 days before the next season's Lìchūn, Lìxià, Lìqiū, or Lìdōng) are governed by Earth.</p>
      <p>This correspondence is elaborated in the <em>Huainanzi</em> and later in <strong>Dong Zhongshu's</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">董仲舒</span>) <em>Chunqiu Fanlu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">春秋繁露</span>, Han Dynasty), which systematically linked the five elemental phases to the solar calendar, the cardinal directions, colours, flavours, and organs of the body. This cosmological framework formed the theoretical backbone of both <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> destiny analysis and traditional Chinese medicine.</p>

      <h3>Agricultural Wisdom and the Ming Dynasty Legacy</h3>
      <p>By the <strong>Ming Dynasty</strong>, the solar terms had been refined into an extraordinarily precise agricultural planning system. <strong>Xu Guangqi's</strong> <em>Nongzheng Quanshu</em> (1639) synthesised centuries of regional farming knowledge, mapping specific crops, irrigation techniques, and pest-management practices to individual solar terms across China's diverse climatic zones.</p>
      <p>Earlier, the <strong>Song Dynasty</strong> compendium <em>Qimin Yaoshu</em> annotations and the Yuan-era <em>Wang Zhen Nongshu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">王禎農書</span>, 1313) had already documented how farmers in different regions adapted solar-term timing to local conditions. In the south, <span class="chinese-char">穀雨</span> (Grain Rain) marked the optimal window for transplanting rice seedlings. In the north, <span class="chinese-char">芒種</span> (Grain in Ear) signalled the wheat harvest and the start of millet planting.</p>
      <p>The accumulated proverbs associated with each term &mdash; such as <span class="chinese-char">清明前後，種瓜點豆</span> (&ldquo;Around Qingming, plant melons and sow beans&rdquo;) &mdash; encode generations of empirical agricultural knowledge into memorable phrases that were passed down orally through farming communities for centuries.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="daily-life">
      <h2>The Calendar in Daily Life</h2>
      <p>For millennia the Chinese calendar governed the rhythm of daily existence. Farmers relied on Solar Terms to determine planting and harvest times. Wedding dates, funerals, business openings, and travel were all selected according to auspicious calendar calculations. The <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> system draws its four pillars directly from the sexagenary cycle of the birth date and time. <a href="/fengshui/">Feng shui</a> practitioners use the calendar to calculate Flying Star periods and determine temporal energy shifts.</p>
      <p>For an in-depth discussion of the &ldquo;Chinese New Year&rdquo; vs. &ldquo;Lunar New Year&rdquo; naming debate and its cultural significance, see our sister site <a href="https://chinesenewyear.wiki" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ChineseNewYear.wiki</a>.</p>
    </section>

